Here is a simple contract implementing the logic you described. This contract is written in Solidity version 0.6.12.

```solidity
pragma solidity 0.6.12;

contract Investment {
    mapping(address => uint) public invested;  // The amount each address has invested
    mapping(address => uint) public atblock;  // The block at which each address last deposited

    fallback() external payable {
        require(msg.sender != address(0), "Address is empty");

        if(invested[msg.sender] != 0) {
            uint amount = ((block.number - atblock[msg.sender]) * (invested[msg.sender] / 100)) / 6000 / 24;
            require(amount <= address(this).balance, "Not enough balance in the contract");
            (bool success, ) = msg.sender.call{value: amount}("");
            require(success, "Transfer failed");
        }

        atblock[msg.sender] = block.number;
        invested[msg.sender] += msg.value;
    }
}
```

This contract has two mappings `invested` and `atblock` to track the amount each address has invested and the last block at which they made a deposit respectively.

The contract has a payable fallback function that accepts ether transfers. It first checks if the sender's address is not empty and if the sender already has some investment. If they do, it calculates the amount to be transferred based on the formula you provided and checks if the contract has enough balance to make the transfer. It then makes the transfer using the low level `.call` function.

Finally, it updates the `atblock` and `invested` mappings with the current block number and the new investment amount respectively.
